<p><strong>Duck breast with cherry gastrique</strong> represents the ultimate Oregon Pinot Noir pairing. The wine's natural cherry and cranberry notes amplify the sauce while its acidity balances the duck's richness. The silky tannins complement the meat's texture without competing.</p>

<p><strong>Aged Oregon cheeses</strong> like Rogue River Blue or aged goat cheese from local creameries create sophisticated pairings. The wine's acidity cuts through creamy textures while its fruit notes provide sweet counterpoints to tangy, aged flavors.</p>

<p><strong>Coq au vin</strong> made with Oregon Pinot Noir creates a perfect flavor circle—the wine's earthy complexity enhances the braised chicken while echoing the cooking wine. Add local chanterelles for an extra layer of terroir expression.</p>

<p class="text-wine-700 italic">The key to pairing Oregon Pinot Noir lies in matching its elegance rather than competing with intensity. Think complementary textures and flavors that enhance rather than mask the wine's subtle complexity.</p>

