<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Oregon Pinot Noir and Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oregon Pinot Noir typically displays more upfront fruit character with riper berry flavors, while Burgundy tends to be more earth-driven with higher acidity and mineral complexity. Oregon's warmer climate produces wines with slightly higher alcohol (13-14%) compared to Burgundy's typical 12.5-13%, though both share the grape's signature silky tannins and aromatic complexity. Oregon winemakers often use more new French oak than their Burgundian counterparts, adding subtle vanilla and spice notes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Oregon AVA produces the best Pinot Noir for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yamhill-Carlton AVA produces some of Oregon's most approachable Pinot Noirs, with consistently ripe fruit flavors and smooth tannins that don't require extensive aging. The warmer sites and well-draining soils create wines with excellent fruit-to-acid balance, making them food-friendly and easy to enjoy young. Producers like Elk Cove and Anne Amie from this region offer excellent entry-level examples under $30.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I age Oregon Pinot Noir before drinking?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Oregon Pinot Noirs are enjoyable within 2-3 years of release, but premium bottlings from top producers like Domaine Drouhin or Archery Summit can benefit from 5-8 years of cellaring. The key is looking for wines with good acidity and structured tannins – these will develop complex secondary flavors of forest floor, leather, and dried herbs with time. Entry-level Oregon Pinot Noirs under $25 are typically made for immediate consumption and don't require aging.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What food pairs best with Oregon Pinot Noir's unique flavor profile?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oregon Pinot Noir's bright acidity and medium body make it exceptional with Pacific Northwest salmon, particularly when grilled or cedar-plank roasted. The wine's earthy undertones complement wild mushroom dishes, while its fruit-forward character works beautifully with duck breast or pork tenderloin. The natural acidity also makes it an excellent match for dishes with cranberry or cherry-based sauces, highlighting the wine's own red fruit characteristics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Oregon Pinot Noir worth the price compared to California options?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oregon Pinot Noir generally offers better value than comparable California Pinot Noir, especially in the $20-40 range where Oregon producers consistently deliver complex, terroir-driven wines. While premium Oregon bottles can reach $60-100, they typically show more restraint and food-friendliness than similarly priced California wines. The cooler Oregon climate produces wines with natural balance that don't rely on excessive oak or manipulation, often resulting in more elegant expressions of Pinot Noir character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when serving Oregon Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serving Oregon Pinot Noir too warm is the most common error – these wines show best at 60-62°F, not room temperature. At warmer temperatures, the alcohol becomes prominent and masks the delicate aromatics that make Oregon Pinot Noir special. Decanting is rarely necessary for most Oregon Pinot Noirs under 5 years old, and over-aerating can actually diminish their subtle perfume and elegance.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Oregon Pinot Noir producers offer the best value under $30?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">A to Z Wineworks consistently produces excellent Oregon Pinot Noir under $20 that showcases true varietal character and regional terroir. Willamette Valley Vineyards offers reliable quality in the $25-30 range, while Erath provides accessible wines that demonstrate classic Oregon style without breaking the bank. These producers focus on blending fruit from multiple vineyard sites, creating consistent, well-balanced wines that represent excellent introductions to Oregon Pinot Noir.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does Oregon Pinot Noir compare to New Zealand Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oregon Pinot Noir tends to be more structured and earthy compared to New Zealand's brighter, more herbaceous style, particularly from Central Otago. Oregon wines typically show deeper color and more pronounced tannins due to the longer, warmer growing season, while New Zealand Pinot Noir often displays distinctive spice notes and higher natural acidity. Both regions produce excellent cool-climate expressions, but Oregon generally offers more Burgundian-style complexity, while New Zealand emphasizes pure fruit expression and aromatic intensity.</p>
